data.content:
Three breaking changes affect your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts expression trees

The setter parameter changed from `Expression<Func<…>>` to `Func<…>`. Your manual expression tree code won't compile. Replace it with the much simpler non-expression lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` needed.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate names are now uniquified.** If `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared a `Street` column (silent data corruption risk), EF 10 auto-appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep the old shared-column behavior, pin names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **If you have existing migrations**, either approach (pin old names or generate a new migration) works — but check that column renames don't break production data.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. This carries the redacted SQL for logging (inlined constants are scrubbed unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on):

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** method signatures in your implementation to add this parameter.
